On day one, we sold about 300 copies.

514
00:23:11,104 --> 00:23:13,765
On day two, we sold about 400 copies.

515
00:23:13,985 --> 00:23:16,006
But then on day three, we already

516
00:23:16,046 --> 00:23:17,486
started selling less and less copies.

517
00:23:17,526 --> 00:23:18,086
We sold 200, and then 150.

518
00:23:20,629 --> 00:23:23,470
and then 120, and then 90.

519
00:23:25,110 --> 00:23:27,291
At this time, there was a tool,

520
00:23:27,731 --> 00:23:29,071
well, the tool still exists,

521
00:23:29,851 --> 00:23:31,151
but we'll talk about that another time.

522
00:23:31,831 --> 00:23:33,652
But the games that we looked at on this tool

523
00:23:34,652 --> 00:23:36,673
had a lot of information about sales data

524
00:23:37,433 --> 00:23:39,513
and how much general sales that you would expect

525
00:23:40,413 --> 00:23:43,014
games to have during certain time windows.

526
00:23:44,274 --> 00:23:45,854
And we had noticed that a lot of other games,

527
00:23:46,315 --> 00:23:48,155
whether it's full release or early access,

528
00:23:48,415 --> 00:23:49,095
it doesn't really matter.

529
00:23:50,719 --> 00:23:52,680
Most of the sales happened in the first two weeks.

530
00:23:53,821 --> 00:23:56,562
And so we were like, hmm, what's gonna happen?

531
00:23:58,122 --> 00:24:02,324
So what were we doing during these two initial weeks?

532
00:24:03,344 --> 00:24:04,865
Nothing too special actually.

533
00:24:05,505 --> 00:24:06,725
Although our sales weren't very good,

534
00:24:06,846 --> 00:24:07,986
we just kinda kept working.

535
00:24:08,926 --> 00:24:10,227
After all, the game is in early access.

536
00:24:10,487 --> 00:24:12,328
It's not done yet.

537
00:24:12,748 --> 00:24:14,268
Surely the game will be successful

538
00:24:14,809 --> 00:24:15,849
once we get into full release.

539
00:24:16,685 --> 00:24:18,046
working on the game was comfortable,

540
00:24:18,346 --> 00:24:20,407
because finally, instead of promoting the game,

541
00:24:20,547 --> 00:24:21,788
we could get back to working on the game,

542
00:24:22,048 --> 00:24:23,689
and that's kind of like what we wanted to do

543
00:24:23,709 --> 00:24:25,150
this whole time, right, is work on the game,

544
00:24:25,691 --> 00:24:26,331
and finish the game.

545
00:24:27,672 --> 00:24:29,213
So we were kind of tired of all these,

546
00:24:29,233 --> 00:24:30,974
like, making these promotion GIFs,

547
00:24:31,755 --> 00:24:34,516
sending out keys, finding people to give keys to,

548
00:24:34,677 --> 00:24:35,457
setting up a store.

549
00:24:35,577 --> 00:24:37,098
Setting up a store requires a lot of things,

550
00:24:37,158 --> 00:24:39,880
descriptions, screenshots, things like that, and so.

551
00:24:41,240 --> 00:24:43,703
And on top of this, since our game was in early access,

552
00:24:43,823 --> 00:24:46,086
we promised to release a patch every single week.

553
00:24:46,987 --> 00:24:49,309
And this was to keep adding content, balance the game,

554
00:24:49,730 --> 00:24:51,592
fix the bug, and get the game to completion.

555
00:24:52,753 --> 00:24:54,796
So, nothing had really changed.

556
00:24:54,896 --> 00:24:55,937
We went back to working on the game.

557
00:24:56,377 --> 00:24:58,400
And we were doing everything exactly the same way,

558
00:24:58,560 --> 00:25:00,202
except we were pushing new builds to Steam

559
00:25:00,242 --> 00:25:00,803
every single week.

560
00:25:02,571 --> 00:25:06,015
Funny story, about nine months after early access release,

561
00:25:06,515 --> 00:25:08,517
we found out that our early access blurb

562
00:25:08,597 --> 00:25:10,700
on the Steam store page said that

563
00:25:10,800 --> 00:25:12,341
we would be patching every two weeks.

564
00:25:12,822 --> 00:25:15,344
So we decided, apparently, to patch twice as often.

565
00:25:17,647 --> 00:25:18,928
So we noticed that a lot of reviews

566
00:25:19,849 --> 00:25:21,671
mentioned that they saw their favorite streamer

567
00:25:21,711 --> 00:25:23,733
play the game, so they encouraged them to buy the game.

568
00:25:24,610 --> 00:25:25,850
And so this was probably Keymailer,

569
00:25:26,050 --> 00:25:27,191
so he said, good job, Keymailer.

570
00:25:27,811 --> 00:25:29,652
So I put a little promotion here.

571
00:25:29,672 --> 00:25:31,592
It says, Keymailer is great, five out of five.

572
00:25:32,033 --> 00:25:33,733
If you work for Keymailer, you may use this quote.

573
00:25:36,014 --> 00:25:36,254
Okay?

574
00:25:36,614 --> 00:25:41,536
So this encouraged us to send out more keys via Keymailer.

575
00:25:42,617 --> 00:25:46,718
This was probably our best investment when it came to time,

576
00:25:47,398 --> 00:25:49,539
in terms of what we were doing to promote the game,

577
00:25:50,119 --> 00:25:51,180
and money-wise, which was $150.

578
00:25:52,791 --> 00:25:54,492
when it came to marketing slash advertising.

579
00:25:55,193 --> 00:25:57,535
Keymailer also felt like a more genuine way to reach players.

580
00:25:58,375 --> 00:26:00,237
Reviewers didn't need to leave positive reviews.

581
00:26:00,457 --> 00:26:01,578
They were just given a free key.

582
00:26:02,178 --> 00:26:04,900
And they were, we just explained what the game is,

583
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:06,681
and they were given a free key.

584
00:26:06,781 --> 00:26:08,242
If they didn't want to play or review it,

585
00:26:08,263 --> 00:26:09,023
they didn't have to.

586
00:26:10,004 --> 00:26:12,306
So, and nothing implied that it had to be positive.

587
00:26:12,486 --> 00:26:14,507
So, if they wanted to play the game, they would play it.

588
00:26:15,502 --> 00:26:18,143
YouTube content creators started making some videos,

589
00:26:18,743 --> 00:26:20,764
and then a few Twitch streamers also started streaming

590
00:26:20,784 --> 00:26:21,845
a game quite regularly.

591
00:26:22,365 --> 00:26:24,786
These were like recurring streamers,

592
00:26:24,986 --> 00:26:26,567
so someone who started playing earlier

593
00:26:26,987 --> 00:26:28,908
would still be playing the game for a few weeks.

594
00:26:29,708 --> 00:26:32,049
And then it turns out the streamer community

595
00:26:32,069 --> 00:26:34,931
is actually pretty tight-knit, which is a good thing.

596
00:26:36,011 --> 00:26:37,352
Their friends started streaming the game,

597
00:26:37,612 --> 00:26:38,993
and then their friends started streaming the game.

598
00:26:41,863 --> 00:26:44,385
I'm not too sure what compelled the first few people

599
00:26:45,086 --> 00:26:47,828
to start streaming our game or to create YouTube content.

600
00:26:49,810 --> 00:26:50,831
Generally what they said was,

601
00:26:50,851 --> 00:26:54,574
I was given a key to this game and it looked interesting.

602
00:26:55,395 --> 00:26:58,618
It's a bit vague, but maybe a combination of our trailer,

603
00:26:58,818 --> 00:27:00,580
elevator pitch, or screenshots did their job.

604
00:27:00,940 --> 00:27:02,902
But keep in mind that we did send keys to people

605
00:27:03,222 --> 00:27:04,283
who had played similar games.

606
00:27:04,763 --> 00:27:08,046
And those keywords like roguelike, deck builder, and...

607
00:27:08,684 --> 00:27:10,825
single-player games, like single-player rogue-lite games,

608
00:27:10,965 --> 00:27:13,786
I think at the time were very fun and exciting.

609
00:27:13,906 --> 00:27:16,707
So I think that was it, but I can't say for sure.

610
00:27:18,388 --> 00:27:22,150
So our initial success actually came on week three

611
00:27:22,750 --> 00:27:24,051
after our early access launch.

612
00:27:24,251 --> 00:27:26,111
There was a very high-profile streamer in China.

613
00:27:27,068 --> 00:27:29,210
that played our game as a very high-profile streamer.

614
00:27:30,090 --> 00:27:32,111
The video of the stream went past a million views

615
00:27:32,792 --> 00:27:34,733
in a couple of days, and suddenly our game was flooded

616
00:27:34,753 --> 00:27:37,714
with a lot of Chinese players who wanted to play our game,

617
00:27:37,954 --> 00:27:39,075
but they were having a hard time

618
00:27:39,535 --> 00:27:41,556
because the game was only available in English at the time.

619
00:27:43,097 --> 00:27:44,738
More people in the US became interested

620
00:27:45,779 --> 00:27:47,159
because it started showing up

621
00:27:47,219 --> 00:27:48,620
on the global top sellers list.

622
00:27:49,421 --> 00:27:50,741
Many of the streamers who received the game

623
00:27:50,761 --> 00:27:52,262
before early access were still playing,

624
00:27:52,922 --> 00:27:54,643
and all their streamer friends also started playing.

625
00:27:55,135 --> 00:27:57,335
And eventually it reached more content creators.

626
00:27:58,055 --> 00:28:00,376
And then we showed up on top sellers list on Steam.

627
00:28:00,576 --> 00:28:03,576
And then showing up on a top sellers list on Steam

628
00:28:03,596 --> 00:28:04,796
apparently changes everything.

629
00:28:05,777 --> 00:28:09,177
Because we went from pretty good sales to crazy sales.

630
00:28:09,777 --> 00:28:12,238
Around the same time we also went on sale.

631
00:28:13,178 --> 00:28:15,758
And so apparently having a game on sale is also good.

632
00:28:16,098 --> 00:28:17,559
So these all kind of compounded together.

633
00:28:17,579 --> 00:28:21,019
And then this happened.

634
00:28:21,379 --> 00:28:23,060
This blue line spike happened.

635
00:28:23,994 --> 00:28:25,234
And it was great, and everything was,

636
00:28:26,695 --> 00:28:28,055
the game was very popular suddenly.

637
00:28:30,235 --> 00:28:30,695
I would say,

638
00:28:30,715 --> 00:28:35,856
another endorsement by myself, just so you know.

639
00:28:38,477 --> 00:28:39,877
So I would say that most of our success

640
00:28:39,957 --> 00:28:41,878
actually came from people genuinely playing the game

641
00:28:41,898 --> 00:28:42,578
and enjoying the game.

642
00:28:43,358 --> 00:28:45,818
I think that Twitch and products like Twitch

643
00:28:46,519 --> 00:28:47,999
are a godsend for games like ours.

644
00:28:48,904 --> 00:28:53,989
A game that isn't visually beautiful or even interesting on paper can now become wildly popular.

645
00:28:56,432 --> 00:29:01,637
And there's also another game that's similar right now, which is fairly unknown, or maybe it is known.

646
00:29:02,118 --> 00:29:05,522
It's a mod for a game called Dota 2, and it's called Auto Chess.

647
00:29:06,303 --> 00:29:10,007
And although on paper it sounds like a mess, it's a mod for a video game.

648
00:29:10,859 --> 00:29:13,100
and the art style is Dota 2 and you should play it.

649
00:29:13,640 --> 00:29:15,360
And that game is really fun.

650
00:29:15,800 --> 00:29:17,381
And so people are playing it,

651
00:29:18,141 --> 00:29:18,681
and people like,

652
00:29:21,202 --> 00:29:23,683
can't name like Twitch streamers off the top of my head.

653
00:29:23,903 --> 00:29:26,504
Like Amaz and stuff are playing the game on Twitch,

654
00:29:27,224 --> 00:29:28,104
and it's doing really well.

655
00:29:29,164 --> 00:29:30,425
Because streamers talk openly

656
00:29:30,465 --> 00:29:31,605
about what they're thinking about,

657
00:29:32,485 --> 00:29:34,866
I feel that users can play vicariously through streamers

658
00:29:34,906 --> 00:29:36,726
by watching them on top of this.

659
00:29:37,620 --> 00:29:40,142
If these games continually become updated and polished,

660
00:29:40,642 --> 00:29:41,803
why would you ever stop playing them?

661
00:29:43,064 --> 00:29:45,346
While we intentionally designed Slay to be fun to watch,

662
00:29:46,127 --> 00:29:48,068
it was a great coincidence and luck for us

663
00:29:48,709 --> 00:29:51,271
that Twitch was and still is growing as a platform.

664
00:29:53,553 --> 00:29:56,355
So if your game is popular in a format where people watch,

665
00:29:56,896 --> 00:29:59,798
people watch other people play Watch, what did I type here?

666
00:30:02,520 --> 00:30:02,640
OK.

667
00:30:04,282 --> 00:30:06,243
I'm going to go ahead and get Casey.

668
00:30:08,163 --> 00:30:11,064
So to make games that are popular for like streamers

669
00:30:11,185 --> 00:30:12,045
and people who play the game,

670
00:30:13,145 --> 00:30:14,346
instead of focusing on marketing,

671
00:30:14,386 --> 00:30:16,186
we focused on something called marketability.

672
00:30:17,687 --> 00:30:19,047
And this is a bit different from marketing.

673
00:30:19,527 --> 00:30:22,048
Marketability is the ability of a video game

674
00:30:22,088 --> 00:30:23,769
to be sold or marketed.

675
00:30:25,409 --> 00:30:26,870
So our lack of response from trailers,

676
00:30:27,630 --> 00:30:30,151
our screenshots, our press emails, our website work,

677
00:30:31,051 --> 00:30:34,232
was very small in comparison to the response we got

678
00:30:34,292 --> 00:30:35,393
whenever we updated the game.

679
00:30:38,272 --> 00:30:40,573
So we finally got to marketability,

680
00:30:41,653 --> 00:30:42,734
but it's really important.

681
00:30:43,154 --> 00:30:45,775
And that's because the context of why we developed the game

682
00:30:46,496 --> 00:30:48,817
the way we did is so important.

683
00:30:50,438 --> 00:30:52,539
We've been making games a very old-fashioned way.

684
00:30:53,239 --> 00:30:55,621
And the combination of three things, which is streaming,

685
00:30:56,501 --> 00:30:59,162
communities, and the fact that we could update easily

686
00:30:59,322 --> 00:31:02,664
allowed us to take this path of marketability

687
00:31:03,224 --> 00:31:06,006
rather than trying to market the game before we sell the game.

688
00:31:09,757 --> 00:31:12,480
So what we wanted to do was the product sell itself,

689
00:31:13,060 --> 00:31:16,443
which was like, I think this is the dream for developers,

690
00:31:16,643 --> 00:31:17,965
because you just get to work on the game.

691
00:31:19,566 --> 00:31:21,848
And so in order to accomplish this dream,

692
00:31:21,868 --> 00:31:23,289
you need to have a strong pipeline.

693
00:31:24,811 --> 00:31:27,173
I guess to put it simply, it would

694
00:31:27,213 --> 00:31:30,776
be having a good method for acquiring feedback, pushing out

695
00:31:30,856 --> 00:31:33,378
updates, and a good way to talk to your community.

696
00:31:38,992 --> 00:31:40,493
All right, and so for pushing updates,

697
00:31:41,294 --> 00:31:43,295
FlateAspire got an update every single week

698
00:31:44,155 --> 00:31:45,856
on the main branch during early access.

699
00:31:46,657 --> 00:31:49,339
Between November 14th and then January 23rd,

700
00:31:49,479 --> 00:31:51,100
which is when we did the full release,

701
00:31:51,680 --> 00:31:53,161
the game was patched 57 times.

702
00:31:55,382 --> 00:31:56,763
One month after early access,

703
00:31:57,664 --> 00:31:58,944
we also created a beta branch

704
00:31:59,125 --> 00:32:00,686
so that players could get a sneak preview

705
00:32:00,906 --> 00:32:04,448
of upcoming content, bug fixes, and so forth

706
00:32:04,568 --> 00:32:07,170
that we can test out things like experimental features.

707
00:32:08,678 --> 00:32:11,779
We think that having a beta branch is necessary

708
00:32:11,819 --> 00:32:15,180
for weekly patching, because we don't have a dedicated QA team.

709
00:32:16,181 --> 00:32:18,181
Whenever we edit anything, there's

710
00:32:18,201 --> 00:32:19,422
a risk that things could break.

711
00:32:20,062 --> 00:32:22,202
And sometimes we'd be up pretty late,

712
00:32:22,642 --> 00:32:23,803
accidentally breaking stuff.

713
00:32:24,143 --> 00:32:26,143
And then we'd fix that, but then that would actually

714
00:32:26,163 --> 00:32:26,724
break it more.

715
00:32:27,444 --> 00:32:29,664
And then we'd be like, why won't I just roll back?

716
00:32:29,684 --> 00:32:31,325
And if you roll back, you don't have new features,

717
00:32:31,345 --> 00:32:32,265
and now it's not exciting.

718
00:32:32,905 --> 00:32:34,166
So we broke the game a lot.

719
00:32:34,726 --> 00:32:36,646
And I don't think people should be afraid of.

720
00:32:37,535 --> 00:32:38,155
breaking the game.

721
00:32:38,395 --> 00:32:40,336
It's part of, at least for early access.

722
00:32:40,676 --> 00:32:42,957
If it's full release, then it should be pretty stable.

723
00:32:44,298 --> 00:32:46,719
Some pros and cons of weekly patching.

724
00:32:46,779 --> 00:32:47,740
New stuff is always happening.

725
00:32:48,240 --> 00:32:50,001
So new stuff, players are always getting new stuff.

726
00:32:50,021 --> 00:32:51,402
There's always excitement.

727
00:32:52,182 --> 00:32:54,283
And it's very fun to see what players want

728
00:32:54,343 --> 00:32:55,464
and expect from a new patch.

729
00:32:56,064 --> 00:32:57,445
And it also gives us ideas.

730
00:32:57,585 --> 00:33:00,046
Sometimes we're about to work on something

731
00:33:00,426 --> 00:33:01,427
that we think is exciting,

732
00:33:01,907 --> 00:33:02,948
but then the player is like,

733
00:33:03,458 --> 00:33:06,139
you know, it would be really great if they worked on this thing,

734
00:33:06,279 --> 00:33:08,520
and then everyone's like, yeah, I bet they're working on this thing.

735
00:33:09,020 --> 00:33:12,141
And then we're like, yes, we are working on that thing.

736
00:33:12,741 --> 00:33:14,722
That's exactly what we're working on.

737
00:33:15,482 --> 00:33:19,384
And so sometimes, you know, what people want is what drives what we work on.

738
00:33:20,584 --> 00:33:22,665
Also, if you patch weekly,

739
00:33:24,046 --> 00:33:26,767
it's a good time to address problems and discussions

740
00:33:26,787 --> 00:33:28,587
that people are having about the game,

741
00:33:28,807 --> 00:33:29,908
so it can be more transparent.

742
00:33:31,152 --> 00:33:32,312
You can discuss what's coming soon.

743
00:33:33,093 --> 00:33:36,434
And of course, if you need help with anything,

744
00:33:37,175 --> 00:33:41,237
such as for us, we had started localizing the game,

745
00:33:41,997 --> 00:33:43,378
and we needed more people to help us

746
00:33:43,718 --> 00:33:44,698
community translate the game.

747
00:33:45,399 --> 00:33:47,640
And so during these weekly announcements,

748
00:33:47,680 --> 00:33:48,780
we can ask for help and be like,

749
00:33:49,141 --> 00:33:50,321
we're looking for translators,

750
00:33:50,721 --> 00:33:51,902
and we did get a lot of translators,

751
00:33:52,162 --> 00:33:55,064
but we'll talk about that on the localization slide.

752
00:33:56,444 --> 00:33:59,046
For cons, whoops, whoa there, calm down.

753
00:33:59,106 --> 00:33:59,686
For cons.

754
00:34:02,625 --> 00:34:03,625
Oh, it's too zoomed out.

755
00:34:04,265 --> 00:34:04,545
All right.

756
00:34:05,005 --> 00:34:07,386
For cons of weekly patching, I would say that

757
00:34:07,566 --> 00:34:09,826
there are just some features that take longer

758
00:34:09,886 --> 00:34:10,907
to make than one week.

759
00:34:11,747 --> 00:34:13,527
And so if you're working on something like that,

760
00:34:14,488 --> 00:34:15,668
or if you're working on content

761
00:34:15,728 --> 00:34:16,968
that is not ready to be revealed,

762
00:34:17,168 --> 00:34:19,929
you're going to have a patch that's not very exciting.

763
00:34:20,469 --> 00:34:21,769
And so you can have some slow weeks.

764
00:34:23,490 --> 00:34:25,850
Another one is writing up an announcement

765
00:34:26,410 --> 00:34:28,711
and getting it proofread.

766
00:34:30,183 --> 00:34:32,765
It takes a lot of work and then you have to push the patch

767
00:34:33,205 --> 00:34:35,087
and then you have to monitor the patch for issues.

768
00:34:35,627 --> 00:34:37,308
So it was actually costing us

769
00:34:37,588 --> 00:34:38,929
one day of productivity a week.

770
00:34:39,490 --> 00:34:41,171
