00:39:01,033 --> 00:39:02,635
That only happens in video games, I think.

878
00:39:04,130 --> 00:39:04,431
Alright.

879
00:39:06,312 --> 00:39:09,314
So, to make our game more marketable,

880
00:39:09,374 --> 00:39:11,476
we also had a lot of design considerations.

881
00:39:12,456 --> 00:39:14,178
Some of these things are about making a game

882
00:39:14,198 --> 00:39:16,779
with complex mechanics easy to understand.

883
00:39:16,799 --> 00:39:19,481
And this is a really large undertaking.

884
00:39:19,902 --> 00:39:21,983
And it could probably be a talk on its own.

885
00:39:22,804 --> 00:39:25,486
But we're gonna go over just a few of them.

886
00:39:26,086 --> 00:39:28,228
Card games have a rich history of complex mechanics.

887
00:39:29,288 --> 00:39:30,509
There's a bunch of different layers,

888
00:39:30,529 --> 00:39:31,770
there's a bunch of different interactions.

889
00:39:32,571 --> 00:39:33,311
Fortunately for us.

890
00:39:34,300 --> 00:39:36,861
we could leverage existing mechanics and terminology

891
00:39:37,461 --> 00:39:38,842
in these games for our game.

892
00:39:39,782 --> 00:39:41,523
Because Slay the Spire was always intended

893
00:39:41,563 --> 00:39:42,983
to be just a digital card game,

894
00:39:43,704 --> 00:39:46,225
we were allowed to keep the visual clutter to a minimum.

895
00:39:47,545 --> 00:39:49,966
Some examples of digital card games are

896
00:39:50,726 --> 00:39:52,907
that the rules are enforced programmatically.

897
00:39:53,728 --> 00:39:55,568
So if you wanted to take a card

898
00:39:56,209 --> 00:39:57,149
and do something strange with it,

899
00:39:57,329 --> 00:40:00,250
like if you wanted to take a card from your draw pile

900
00:40:00,490 --> 00:40:01,431
and discard it immediately,

901
00:40:02,025 --> 00:40:04,107
You couldn't just do that, because the game would say no.

902
00:40:04,808 --> 00:40:05,869
The code doesn't allow it, right?

903
00:40:07,330 --> 00:40:09,332
Complex mechanics, such as statuses,

904
00:40:10,433 --> 00:40:11,754
things like keywords for each card.

905
00:40:12,294 --> 00:40:14,637
These definitions would appear when you hover over a card.

906
00:40:15,077 --> 00:40:19,061
So a card can be like, apply to vulnerable.

907
00:40:19,081 --> 00:40:21,463
And you'd be like, what's apply to vulnerable mean?

908
00:40:21,723 --> 00:40:23,344
And you hover over it and say, vulnerable

909
00:40:23,424 --> 00:40:25,146
is enemies take 50% more damage.

910
00:40:25,246 --> 00:40:27,188
And you're like, oh, thanks, keyword tip person.

911
00:40:29,090 --> 00:40:32,031
You can also show tutorials or blurbs if the player does something wrong.

912
00:40:33,191 --> 00:40:37,073
In the GIF here, you can see that our player is trying to play these cards.

913
00:40:37,373 --> 00:40:38,373
Come on, loop please.

914
00:40:39,593 --> 00:40:42,174
So it's like, oh look, we're playing a strike and we're trying to play this bash.

915
00:40:42,735 --> 00:40:43,875
Oh, we can't, we're out of energy.

916
00:40:44,655 --> 00:40:45,456
I'm gonna try again.

917
00:40:45,476 --> 00:40:49,477
Oh, no you can't, you really can't.

918
00:40:49,717 --> 00:40:51,378
So, we show like some more like...

919
00:40:53,181 --> 00:40:54,562
We show tips that have more words

920
00:40:55,143 --> 00:40:56,985
and try to make sure the player understands what's going on

921
00:40:57,865 --> 00:40:59,487
if they continue to not understand something.

922
00:40:59,607 --> 00:41:01,189
So that's something we've gotten from

923
00:41:02,030 --> 00:41:03,791
just like playtesting more in person.

924
00:41:04,752 --> 00:41:06,254
Because sometimes you would see like thought bubble

925
00:41:06,294 --> 00:41:07,775
that says, I cannot play this.

926
00:41:08,055 --> 00:41:09,076
And sometimes they would ignore it.

927
00:41:09,637 --> 00:41:10,678
So we added those kind of things.

928
00:41:12,720 --> 00:41:14,582
Things like, what other things that are useful

929
00:41:14,622 --> 00:41:15,362
for digital card games?

930
00:41:16,255 --> 00:41:17,617
You can view your deck instantly.

931
00:41:17,717 --> 00:41:19,999
You just push a button, and you'll see a grid of cards.

932
00:41:20,139 --> 00:41:20,920
You can see your whole deck.

933
00:41:21,140 --> 00:41:23,121
You don't have to fan through them individually.

934
00:41:23,882 --> 00:41:27,065
The game shuffles cards for you, things of that nature.

935
00:41:27,085 --> 00:41:30,568
In a video game, there's also a bunch of other stuff

936
00:41:30,588 --> 00:41:30,868
you can do.

937
00:41:30,888 --> 00:41:31,949
There's so much things you can do.

938
00:41:31,969 --> 00:41:33,351
There's so much UX design.

939
00:41:34,011 --> 00:41:35,052
If you look closely at the image,

940
00:41:35,072 --> 00:41:37,634
you can see things like the cards that are playable

941
00:41:37,795 --> 00:41:38,816
have a blue outline.

942
00:41:39,736 --> 00:41:41,918
The cards where you don't have enough energy, the text is red.

943
00:41:43,504 --> 00:41:45,305
And there's also audio and visual cues.

944
00:41:45,825 --> 00:41:47,585
We make the sound when you can't play a card.

945
00:41:48,305 --> 00:41:50,046
When you play a card, there'll be a trail,

946
00:41:50,146 --> 00:41:52,426
and the card will fly into like discard pile.

947
00:41:52,786 --> 00:41:56,827
When the card, you know, when cards need to shuffle,

948
00:41:57,188 --> 00:41:59,288
there'll be like an animation of all the cards

949
00:41:59,328 --> 00:42:01,049
going from discard pile into draw pile.

950
00:42:01,629 --> 00:42:02,569
So those kind of things here.

951
00:42:03,889 --> 00:42:04,549
Less words, good.

952
00:42:05,897 --> 00:42:08,138
What we mean by this is to make our,

953
00:42:08,918 --> 00:42:11,799
so our game was focused a lot on its content

954
00:42:11,859 --> 00:42:13,919
and playing the game, and it wasn't very lore heavy.

955
00:42:14,859 --> 00:42:16,120
However, there is some lore,

956
00:42:16,880 --> 00:42:17,900
and you can get through this lore,

957
00:42:18,560 --> 00:42:20,541
but we also didn't want to make it mandatory.

958
00:42:22,141 --> 00:42:24,121
Things like events in our game,

959
00:42:25,102 --> 00:42:26,982
you don't need to read all the words,

960
00:42:27,182 --> 00:42:29,143
you can just look at the options,

961
00:42:29,323 --> 00:42:31,063
and the options tell you exactly what's going to happen.

962
00:42:31,623 --> 00:42:34,924
And this was very important for the streamability of the game.

963
00:42:35,878 --> 00:42:37,479
because then players could look at the options

964
00:42:37,499 --> 00:42:39,320
that are available and then follow those options.

965
00:42:41,601 --> 00:42:42,821
Alright, so for localization.

966
00:42:44,302 --> 00:42:45,703
Localization, if you don't know,

967
00:42:45,783 --> 00:42:48,524
is translating your game to multiple languages

968
00:42:48,584 --> 00:42:50,025
so people in other countries can play the game.

969
00:42:50,725 --> 00:42:54,307
This is our sales data from two weeks after the EA release

970
00:42:55,768 --> 00:42:57,008
to six weeks after release.

971
00:42:58,529 --> 00:43:01,691
Things that are really important here is that China.

972
00:43:02,968 --> 00:43:05,729
made up 42% of all the sales during this time.

973
00:43:06,429 --> 00:43:08,370
And if you combine all the English-speaking countries

974
00:43:08,790 --> 00:43:10,250
on this pie chart, it's 41%.

975
00:43:10,890 --> 00:43:13,311
And this was before any localization

976
00:43:13,351 --> 00:43:14,291
was available in the game.

977
00:43:14,631 --> 00:43:16,191
So there were a lot of confused players.

978
00:43:17,531 --> 00:43:19,352
And so we started our localization efforts.

979
00:43:19,832 --> 00:43:21,272
And the game is now translated to,

980
00:43:23,273 --> 00:43:24,813
actually I added one or two more recently.

981
00:43:25,353 --> 00:43:28,193
So it should be around 16 to 18 languages.

982
00:43:28,874 --> 00:43:30,334
So we moved forward one year.

983
00:43:31,472 --> 00:43:32,272
we can see what happens.

984
00:43:32,972 --> 00:43:34,933
You definitely want to plan ahead for localization.

985
00:43:35,473 --> 00:43:37,394
If you are a programmer, you understand

986
00:43:37,434 --> 00:43:38,855
what it means to hard-code strings.

987
00:43:39,815 --> 00:43:42,596
Don't hard-code strings, although we didn't.

988
00:43:44,157 --> 00:43:45,738
And make your game localizable.

989
00:43:45,758 --> 00:43:47,639
You should always try to make your game

990
00:43:47,759 --> 00:43:49,780
available to as much people as possible, for sure.

991
00:43:51,000 --> 00:43:52,601
There's also other considerations to make.

992
00:43:53,261 --> 00:43:57,803
A lot of engines would render certain languages differently,

993
00:43:57,943 --> 00:43:59,864
certain texts differently, certain fonts differently.

994
00:44:00,405 --> 00:44:03,906
If you include all the fonts, your game can get pretty big pretty fast.

995
00:44:05,006 --> 00:44:07,427
Some fonts have very strange text formatting rules,

996
00:44:07,787 --> 00:44:09,227
such as a lack of spaces.

997
00:44:10,167 --> 00:44:12,448
And since our game also incorporated symbols

998
00:44:12,868 --> 00:44:15,049
and keywords that have special logic appendants to them,

999
00:44:16,069 --> 00:44:18,070
it was very, very difficult to translate our game.

1000
00:44:18,290 --> 00:44:21,230
And we're still working on a few languages as well.

1001
00:44:22,211 --> 00:44:24,091
So we worked with community translators.

1002
00:44:24,791 --> 00:44:29,593
We actually initially started with a professional localization company.

1003
00:44:30,713 --> 00:44:34,514
And because we released a patch every week with new content,

1004
00:44:35,055 --> 00:44:36,115
it would always be outdated.

1005
00:44:36,135 --> 00:44:38,256
It would always be behind by two or three weeks.

1006
00:44:39,056 --> 00:44:42,578
And on top of that, a lot of the community translations

1007
00:44:43,038 --> 00:44:44,799
were a bit better because they played the game.

1008
00:44:44,979 --> 00:44:49,481
And so a game with a lot of technical keywords and terms

1009
00:44:50,701 --> 00:44:52,822
just made more sense for somebody who played the game.

1010
00:44:53,702 --> 00:44:55,323
I think that it's very important for card games

1011
00:44:55,723 --> 00:44:58,084
that anyone who translates it knows what's going on.

1012
00:45:00,713 --> 00:45:04,914
All right, so lesson here is don't ignore China

1013
00:45:04,934 --> 00:45:08,755
and translate your game to a bunch of languages.

1014
00:45:08,775 --> 00:45:10,435
I was going to point out to some stuff

1015
00:45:10,515 --> 00:45:12,496
and be like, wow, look, all these other languages that.

1016
00:45:13,056 --> 00:45:14,736
So there's a bunch of extra countries

1017
00:45:14,796 --> 00:45:16,636
here that were not available in the previous slide.

1018
00:45:17,357 --> 00:45:20,197
You can see in this slide that I can't see it anymore

1019
00:45:20,497 --> 00:45:22,358
because my eyes are not that good.

1020
00:45:23,170 --> 00:45:25,491
But what happens is, after you translate the game,

1021
00:45:25,811 --> 00:45:28,392
countries like Korea, Japan, Russia,

1022
00:45:28,412 --> 00:45:29,772
all start buying your game as well.

1023
00:45:30,273 --> 00:45:33,254
And they make up quite a sizable amount of players.

